{
  "doc_id": "42974",
  "text": "In a number of vertebrates, the expression of alternative pale and melanic phenotypes is associated with mutations at the Mc1r or extension locus. Gain-of-function mutations responsible for constitutive active MC1Rs result in a higher production of eumelanin pigments and thus darker colouration in wild-type animals. On the contrary, loss-of-function mutations produce lighter melanin colouration (see reviews in [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Apart from producing melanin pigments, Mc1r is commonly considered to induce few other physiological effects. As a consequence, the evolution and maintenance of MC1R-dependent colour morphs may often be the direct effect of natural selection exerted on colouration itself rather than being an indirect effect of selection acting on genetically correlated traits [CITATION_3] . However, MC1R is not only expressed in the melanocytes of developing feather buds and hair follicles [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] ), but also in various cells of the immune system such as monocytes, macrophages [CITATION_6] , neutrophils [CITATION_7] , B lymphocytes, natural killer cells and a subset of cytotoxic and CD8 + T cells [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . This suggests that MC1R could have immunological consequences. Accordingly, the melanocortin a-MSH has potent and broad effects on inflammation, which are in part exerted when bound to MC1R [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . Activation of MC1R causes a collective reduction in the pro-inflammatory molecules (IL1, -2, -4, -6, -12, -13, TNF, NF-jB and prostaglandins) and an increase in the anti-inflammatory mediators involved in the inflammatory process [CITATION_12] and is critical for the induction of cytotoxicity in human and murine CD8 + T cells [CITATION_13] . Based on the hypothesis that MC1R is not only involved in the expression of melaninbased colouration but also in immunological processes, we derive the prediction that alternative colour morphs may differ in their cell-mediated response, i.e. pale morphs tending towards inflammatory types of immunity and dark morphs tending towards anti-inflammatory, in species in which variation in melanin-based colouration is due to mutations at Mc1r.",
